Paper review

1) A single Bayesian Network classifier for monitoring with unknown classes

Authors: A. Stout, A. Cohen, S. Vernon, A. Kobi.

Date: 2019

Ref : Atoui et al. (2019)

The authors investigate the use of BN to create a classifier for monitoring systems with unknown classes. They employ Conditional Gaussian Networks (CGN), where each node represents either a discrete or Gaussian random variable linked to multivariate random variables (RV). Their approach involves graphical analysis and a quadratic statistic to determine the class of each multivariate observation, utilizing a control limit (CL) for classification.

The paper delves into detailed analysis, providing insights into the fault detection and diagnosis algorithm, including exclusion criteria. Various structures are explored, such as simpler BN structures and their association with CGN. The effectiveness of the proposed system is demonstrated and evaluated using the complex Tennessee Eastman Process (TEP).

Further research is suggested to expand the proposed approach to other data-driven CGN, develop new algorithms to handle multiple faults, and explore more complex BN structures for integration.

2) Application of Bayesian Networks in Reliability Evaluation

Authors: B.Â Cai, X. Kong, Y. Liu, J. Lin, X. Yuan, H. Xu, R. Ji.

Date: 2019

Ref : Cai et al. (2020)

The authors review the use of BN over the past decades, highlighting their strengths in modeling complex systems and handling uncertainties. Like comprehensive review of the industrial application in reliability field. The new feature introduced in the paper is a classification framework for BN in reliability evaluation. This frameworkÂ categorisesÂ BN based on the objects of reliability evaluation (hardware, software), which provides a structured approach to applying BN across various industrial contexts. This systematic classification helps in better understanding and implementing BN for different reliability evaluation tasks, enhancing the practical application and effectiveness of BN in real-world scenarios.

The paper discusses various case studies, demonstrating the practical implementation of BN in different industrial contexts. However, there are some limitations, firstÂ the accuracy of BN heavily relies on the availability of sufficient and high-quality data, which can be a significant constraint. Second, applying BN to very large and complex systems poses computational challenges, making it difficult to manage and analyseÂ such systems effectively. Third, there is a need for further research to integrate BN with other reliability evaluation methods, which could enhance their accuracy and applicability in diverse industrial contexts. Addressing these limitations is essential for improving the practical use of BN in reliability assessments.

3) Rational Irrationality: Modeling Climate Change Belief Polarization Using Bayesian Networks

Authors: J. Cook, S. Lewandowsky

Date: 2016

Ref : Cook and Lewandowsky (2016)

This paper examines belief polarization, which occurs when two individuals interpret the same evidence and update their beliefs in opposite directions. This phenomenon represents the irrational aspect of the study. The researchers use Bayesian networks to simulate belief polarization, representing the rational aspect.

The study focuses on climate change beliefs in two countries, Australia and the USA. Four groups of variables were used to illustrate different factors: W (worldview/free market support), T (trust in climate scientists), H (belief in human-caused global warming), and E (evidence from scientific consensus). The relationships between these variables are modeled as follows: W-T, W-H, T-E, H-E.

The aim was to determine if individuals with different worldviews (W) exhibit belief polarization when presented with scientific evidence, considering varying levels of trust in climate scientists and belief in human-caused global warming.

Data analysis was conducted using R, modeling ANOVA tests for each variable combination. Significant differences were found between the two countries. Bayesian networks were then fitted to each countryâs data, resulting in unique sets of Bayesian network parameters for each.

The study found that worldview is a dominant influence on climate beliefs and that providing consensus information increases the perception of consensus. Among U.S. participants, the consensus intervention led to increased distrust in scientists among those with a particular worldview when informed about the scientific consensus.

A limitation of the study is the small effect sizes of the experimental manipulation compared to the large effect of worldview, which may be due to the brief nature of the manipulation.

5) Applications of Bayesian networks and Petri nets in safety, reliability, and risk assessments: A review

Authors: S. Kabir, Y. Papadopoulos

Date: 2019

Ref : Kabir and Papadopoulos (2019)

This paper is a review of how to prevent risk by controlling the parameter of reliability and risk assessments in complex systems by using Bayesian networks and Petri nets. Even if half of the paper will be on petri nets, itâs interesting to see the link between those two methods. We can also mention the use of markov chain to do the same surveillance. It also explain the links between other methods to Bayesian networks, for example how to go from a fault tree to a Bayesian network (the mapping process).

Itâs re-explaining the advantages of Bayesian networks and why using them in a problem related to safety and risk assessment. The main advantage of Bayesian networks over the other existing approaches is their polyvalency, they can offer different functionality such as predictive and diagnostic analysis model, updating, and optimization. Also, Bayesian network can applied both discrete and continuous model of time.

They also explain the process of creation of a Bayesian network, following these steps:

I. Identify variables -> identify network structure -> Express as statistical variables

II. Specify conditional probabilities

III. Enter evidence -> Propagate -> Interprete results

The major limitations of Bayesian network aplications are that the guideline we use to create the nodes will define the result at the end, so to ensure a coherent model we should take care of the few first steps. Also, if the parent-child relationships are not properly defined, the model can be more complex to analyse.
